heterodyning concepts.

69
00:05:55.718 --> 00:06:02.810
And after that, Edwin Armstrong
went on to invent FM radio.

70
00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:07.880
This was one of his most
brilliant inventions.

71
00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:12.170
So if you had a signal with,
say, a bandwidth of about 5 or

72
00:06:12.170 --> 00:06:18.770
15 kilohertz, and so
that's what you need for audio.

73
00:06:18.770 --> 00:06:26.270
In the AM transmission which is
based on the vacuum tube and

74
00:06:26.270 --> 00:06:30.450
the heterodyning principle,
this is the technique that

75
00:06:30.450 --> 00:06:36.030
RCA was using at the time for all their
radio stations and their receivers.

76
00:06:36.030 --> 00:06:40.501
You need a very small spectrum to
actually send it over the radio.

77
00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:43.590
In simple amplitude modulation,

78
00:06:43.590 --> 00:06:47.600
the bandwidth becomes 2 times
15 kilohertz, 30 kilohertz.

79
00:06:49.472 --> 00:06:54.910
In FM, instead of modulating the carrier,
you actually modulate

80
00:06:54.910 --> 00:07:00.790
the frequency to much higher
value as the frequency increases.

81
00:07:00.790 --> 00:07:06.280
So what this means is there is this
bandwidth expansion that is happening.

82
00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:13.950
So when you modulate a 15 kilohertz
content for transmission in FM radio,

83
00:07:13.950 --> 00:07:20.200
you go up to 75 kilohertz
in commercial effect.

84
00:07:20.200 --> 00:07:25.150
So you end up with about
150 to 200 kilohertz

85
00:07:25.150 --> 00:07:28.350
bandwidth for each radio station.

86
00:07:29.590 --> 00:07:34.902
This was very difficult with the backward
compatibility with AM radio.

87
00:07:34.902 --> 00:07:37.200
There were definitely advantages.

88
00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:41.940
It turns out that by using more bandwidth,

89
00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:45.980
you could get 27 dB of coding gain in FM.

90
00:07:45.980 --> 00:07:50.340
What that means is,
compared to the AM radio,

91
00:07:50.340 --> 00:07:55.860
the noise floor for FM is 500 times lower.

92
00:07:55.860 --> 00:08:00.540
That means you have much
clearer sound quality,

93
00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:04.310
music quality and effect compared to AM.

94
00:08:06.348 --> 00:08:11.340
For Sarnoff, the FM radio was a threat

95
00:08:11.340 --> 00:08:17.050
to the industry that he had built and
deployed.

96
00:08:17.050 --> 00:08:20.540
And of course,
you needed more spectrum for

97
00:08:21.660 --> 00:08:25.920
FM services because you could
not be compatible with AM.

98
00:08:26.970 --> 00:08:34.030
RCA did its best to stop Armstrong
from commercializing FM radio.

99
